{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504610"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:18:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:18:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2348"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2348"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.48,0.25,0.14,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51887"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2348"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37199"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"205"},{"type":"tags","id":"2962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1296"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14408"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18054"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51887"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of increasing difficulty breathing, worse with exertion and when lying flat. She denies cough. She has a medical history of an inherited muscular disorder that has left her wheelchair-bound, and gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Her only medication is pantoprazole 40 mg daily. She is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly short of breath. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 19/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Chest expansion is reduced symmetrically. The percussion note is resonant throughout. There is generally poor air entry bilaterally, but normal breath sounds can be heard throughout the lung fields. Severe kyphoscoliosis is evident.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT scan of the chest","Pulmonary function testing","Chest X-ray","Electromyography","Sleep study"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the clinical presentation, this patient likely has restrictive lung disease secondary to her neuromuscular disorder and kyphoscoliosis, however given her age and symptoms ruling out more common obstructive pathologies such as asthma is still important. Therefore, the most appropriate next investigation is \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary function testing\u003C/strong\u003E. This will allow differentiation between restrictive and obstructive lung disease, as well as determine the severity of the condition. Pulmonary function tests are reproducible and accurate, providing crucial information about lung volumes, capacities, and flow rates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the chest\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate next step. While it can provide detailed imaging of lung parenchyma and pleura, it is not the first-line investigation for suspected restrictive lung disease. CT scanning is more indicated when there is suspicion of interstitial lung disease or when chest X-ray findings are inconclusive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful in this patient\u0027s workup, but it is not the most important next step. While it can show the kyphoscoliosis and potentially reveal any gross lung abnormalities, it won\u0027t provide the functional information that pulmonary function tests can offer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectromyography\u003C/strong\u003E is a test used to evaluate muscle function and the nerves controlling the muscles. While it may be useful in further investigating the patient\u0027s neuromuscular disorder, it is not the most appropriate next step in evaluating her respiratory symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esleep study\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered in the future if there is suspicion of sleep-disordered breathing, which can be associated with neuromuscular disorders and kyphoscoliosis. However, it is not the most appropriate next investigation for evaluating daytime dyspnoea and orthopnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, pulmonary function testing is the most appropriate next step as it will provide crucial information about the type and severity of lung disease, guiding further management and potentially indicating the need for additional investigations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary function testing allows differentiation between restrictive and obstructive lung disease, as well as determining severity.","Kyphoscoliosis and neuromuscular disorders can lead to restrictive lung disease.","Symptoms of restrictive lung disease include dyspnoea on exertion and orthopnoea."],"references":["Ponce MC, Sharma S. Pulmonary Function Tests. In: StatPearls [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482339/","Buyse B, Meersseman W, Demedts M. Treatment of chronic respiratory failure in kyphoscoliosis: oxygen or ventilation? Eur Respir J. 2003 Sep;22(3):525-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14516146/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37199"}},"question":{"data":{"typ